quran[9]{c,v,t,f}:
  23,100,"that I have left behind. I am likely to do good.",footnotes:1:It occurs at several places in the Quran that each of the criminals, after his death till his entry into Hell, and even after that, will plead again and again: Lord, send me back to the world, I will no more disobey Thee, I will now do righteous deeds. See (Surah Al-Anaam, Ayats 27, 28); (Surah Al-Aaraf, Ayat 53); (Surah Ibrahim, Ayats 44, 45); (Surah Ash-Shuara, Ayat 102); (Surah Al-Fatir, Ayat 37);(Surah Az- Zumar, Ayats 58, 59);(Surah Al-Momin, Ayats 10-12), and (Surah Ash-Shura, Ayats 44 )along with the relevant E.Ns.
  23,101,"And then no sooner the Trumpet is blown than there will remain no kinship among them that Day, nor will they ask one another.{1}",footnotes:1:It does not mean that the father will not remain father and the son will not remain son, etc. It only means that they will not be able to help each other, nor shall they be able to inquire about each other as father and son, for each one will be worried and anxious about his own plight. See (Surah Al-Maarij, Ayats 10-14), and (Surah Abasa, Ayats 34- 37).
  23,102,"It will be an Hour when those whose scales are heavy,{1} they alone will attain success;",footnotes:1:That is, those whose good deeds will be heavy and will out-weigh their evil deeds.
  25,46,"So (as the sun rises), We gradually roll up that shade unto Us.{1}",footnotes:1:We annihilate it or cause it to disappear, for everything which is annihilated returns to Allah, because everything comes from Him and returns to Him.
  25,47,"It is Allah Who has made night a garment for you,{1} and sleep the repose (of death), and has made day the time of rising to life.{2}",footnotes:1:The night is a garment in the sense that it covers and hides things.
  25,48,"And He it is Who sends forth the winds as glad tidings, heralding His Mercy. Then We send down pure water{1} from the sky",footnotes:1:That is, such water as is pure and free from all sorts of impurities, germs and poison, which cleanses and washes away filth and becomes a source of life for men, beasts as well as all kinds of plant life.
  26,19,"You spent many years of your life among us and then you committed that deed of yours.{1} You are very ungrateful indeed.",footnotes:1:The allusion is to the incident of murder committed by Moses accidentally.
  26,20,"Moses replied: ",footnotes:1:The word dalalat does not always mean straying away, but it is also used in the sense of ignorance, folly, error, forgetfulness, inadvertence, etc. As mentioned in Surah Al- Qasas, Prophet Moses (peace be upon him) had only given a blow to the Egyptian (Copt) when he saw him beating an Israelite cruelly. A blow does not cause death, nor is it given with the intention of causing death. It was only an accident that the Egyptian died. As such, it was not a case of deliberate murder but of accidental murder. A murder was committed but not intentionally, nor was any weapon used, which is usually employed for murder, or which can cause murder.
  26,21,"Then I fled for fear of you. Then my Lord bestowed wisdom and authority on me{1} and made me one of the Messengers.",footnotes:1:The word hukm means wisdom, knowledge or authority, which is granted by Allah to a Prophet so that he may speak with confidence and power.